map.http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com: Set of homologous sequences

Basic unit of graphs and trees. This class was modified from its original definition (with class restrictions) to avoid multiple statements that relates a Node to a Network (e.g.: RootedTree). In its orignal definition, for each created instance of a Node, an additional statement must be defined to declare that a given node belongs to a Network what is quite verbose. However, we know that sub-nodes of a root node must belong to the same given Rooted Tree (e.g.: HOGs). Therefore, no needs to state sub-nodes to be part of a  RootedTree.

Dataset that provides orthology relations including clusters of orthologs, pairwise orthology relations, and so on.

Examples would be the content of resources such as OMA, InParanoid, TreeFam, PhylomeDB and so on. Each release of the resources is different dataset.
Set of homologous sequences derived from a speciation event.
Set of homologous sequences derived from a duplication event
A database is a data store such as relational, hierarchical and graph databases.
All sequence units (e.g. Gene) that are expressed in some condition (e.g. organ and/or adult stage).

A region (or regions) that includes all of the sequence elements necessary to encode a functional transcript. A gene may include regulatory regions, transcribed regions and/or other functional sequence regions.
Tree with a root node, which is the common ancestor to all the nodes in the tree
An anatomical entity can be an organism part (e.g. brain, blood, liver and so on) or a material anatomical entity such as a cell.
A rank of a taxon.
A sequence unit (e.g. Gene) is expressed in some expression condition (e.g. anatomical entity and/or developmental stage).
A collection of related genes.
This branch will be replaced by, and if necessary merged with an Uberon import in future.
map.http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_00001: A developmental stage is spatiotemporal region encompassing some part of the life cycle of an organism, e.g. blastula stage

map.http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com: A tree whose content is the result of the application of hierarchical clustering to a dataset
A node of a tree whose leaf nodes are sequence units and whose internal nodes are clusters of homologs

A living being, such as an animal, a plant, a bacterium, or a fungus., Any individual living (or previously living) being. Example: animal, human being. An organim is associated to a taxon such as \"Homo Sapiens\", NCBI taxonomy identifier: 9606.
protein or DNA sequence as a unit of comparison
A sequence of amino acids linked by peptide bonds which may lack appreciable tertiary structure and may not be liable to irreversible denaturation.
The taxonomic level represents the taxon at which a group of sequences are considered members of the same cluster of orthologs/paralogs
A tree whose leaf nodes correspond to sequence units (e.g.: genes).
An element of a taxonomy for classifying life forms.

This property was simplified. Original range and domain were removed due to be highly abstracted because it is well-know the domain of discourse: orthology databases.  The rage restriction of this property is defined as a class restriction in (e.g.: orth:Gene).
A sequence unit (e.g.: gene) comes from an organism.
A relation between two objects, in which the first object is produced from the information contained in the second object.
A relation between two objects, in which the first object is produced from the information contained in the second object.
A relation between two objects, in which the first object is produced from the information contained in the second object.
Connects a biological entity to its taxon of origin.
Property that permits to define the membership of a cluster of homologs or a sequence unit to a clusters of homologs.
Property that associates a cluster of homologs with the taxonomic range at which it has been calculated
Property that provides the dataset associated with a gene tree node
Property that permits to define the membership of a cluster of homologs or a sequence unit to a clusters of homologs.
Property that permits to define the membership of a cluster of homologs or a sequence unit to a clusters of homologs.
Property that permits to define the membership of a cluster of homologs or a sequence unit to a clusters of homologs.
Property that provides the dataset associated with a gene tree node
The property links a rooted tree to the specific node that represents the unique root of the tree.
The rank of a taxon.
A sequence unit (e.g.: gene) comes from an organism.

map.http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_00001: x expressed in y if and only if there is a gene expression process (GO:0010467) that occurs in y, and one of the following holds: (i) x is a gene, and x is transcribed into a transcript as part of the gene expression process (ii) x is a transcript, and the transcription of x is part of the gene expression process (iii) x is a mature gene product such as a protein, and x was translated or otherwise processes from a transcript that was transcribed as part of this gene expression process
'neural crest cell'  SubClassOf expresses some 'Wnt1 gene'

map.http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com:
Recommendation: prefer to instatiate absence of gene expression and gene expression experiment condition classes to represent Gene expression data. For example,  rather than materializing this property at the data store level, it shoud be inferred by applying the logical rules:   
rule1- expressed gene(?e),has an expression condition(?e, ?cond), has sequence unit(?e, ?seq) -> is expressed in(?seq, ?cond); 
rule2- expressed gene(?e),has an expression condition(?e, ?cond), has a developmental stage(?cond, ?stage), has sequence unit(?e, ?seq) -> is expressed in(?seq, ?stage)
rule3-  expressed gene(?e),has an expression condition(?e, ?cond), has strain(?cond, ?strain), has sequence unit(?e, ?seq) -> is expressed in(?seq, ?strain)
rule4- expressed gene(?e),has an expression condition(?e, ?cond), has anatomical entity(?cond, ?anat), has sequence unit(?e, ?seq) -> is expressed in(?seq, ?anat)

These rules are currently defined in Genex ontology as a SWRL (Semantic Web Rule Language) rule. It can be tanslated into another semantic web language such as  RIF.

map.http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_00001: holds between two entities when some genome-level process such as gene expression is involved. This includes transcriptional, spliceosomal events. These relations can be used between either macromolecule entities (such as regions of nucleic acid) or between their abstract informational counterparts.
map.http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_00002: Do not use this relation directly. It is intended as a grouping for a diverse set of relations, all involving the genome of an organism
